pull_request.title: Silence curl and simplify quoting
pull_request.body:
## Why was this change made? 🤔

cron on `preservation-catalog-prod-04` was sending email because curl's diagnostic output was being sent to stderr, which caused cron to think something was wrong. This change tells curl to be silent, and removes some of the unneeded quoting so that the cron entries are easier to read. The `:output` for runner_hb was also positioned earlier since curl will be quiet.

The two different styles of resulting cron entries now look like:

```
0 0 * * 3 /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221207173228 && bin/rails runner -e production "PreservedObject.archive_check_expired.find_each(&:audit_moab_version_replication!)" >> /dev/null 2>> log/c2a-err.log && curl --silent https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/rkIdpB'

0 * * * * /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221207173228 && RAILS_ENV=production bundle exec rake --silent "prescat:cache_cleaner:stale_files" >> /var/log/preservation_catalog/zip_cache_cleanup.log && curl --silent https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/2AIqEx'
```

Fixes #2102

## How was this change tested? 🤨

Tested crontab generation on QA.

issue.title: Invalid crontab entry on preservation-catalog-prod-04
issue.body:
Cron on `pres@preservation-catalog-prod-04.stanford.edu` is reporting an error via email:

```
From: root@preservation-catalog-prod-04.stanford.edu (Cron Daemon)
To: pres@preservation-catalog-prod-04.stanford.edu
Subject: Cron <pres@preservation-catalog-prod-04> /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221206133618 && RAILS_ENV=production bundle exec rake prescat:cache_cleaner:stale_files --silent >> /var/log/preservation_catalog/zip_cache_cleanup.log && curl '\''https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/REDACTED'

/bin/bash: -c: line 0: unexpected EOF while looking for matching `''
/bin/bash: -c: line 1: syntax error: unexpected end of file
```

The crontab entry looks like:

```
0 * * * * /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221206133618 && RAILS_ENV=production bundle exec rake prescat:cache_cleaner:stale_files --silent >> /var/log/preservation_catalog/zip_cache_cleanup.log && curl '\''https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/REDACTED'
```

The quoting seems a bit unbalanced? I noticed it is also different than the equivalent HB crontab on `preservation-catalog-prod-02.stanford.edu`:

```
0 1 * * 0 /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221206133618 && bin/rails runner -e production '\''MoabStorageRoot.find_each(&:validate_expired_checksums!)'\'' && curl '\''https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/REDACTED'\'' >> /dev/null 2>> log/cv-err.log'
```

Perhaps this is related to our [recent integration](https://github.com/sul-dlss/preservation_catalog/pull/2075) of HoneyBadger into crontabs?

**User Impact**

It looks like there is little user impact, but if the zips aren't cleaned up presumably a filesystem will fill up and we'll start getting errors in Argo.

**Object(s) In This Error State**

It appears to only be affecting `preservation-catalog-prod-04`.

Steps to Reproduce, if Known:

Run the command in the crontab manually?

**Expected behavior**

For the cron to run without reporting errors via email.

+## Cron check-ins
+Some cron jobs (configured via the whenever gem) are integrated with Honeybadger check-ins. These cron jobs will check-in with HB (via a curl request to an HB endpoint) whenever run. If a cron job does not check-in as expected, HB will alert.
+
+Cron check-ins are configured in the following locations:
+1. `config/schedule.rb`: This specifies which cron jobs check-in and what setting keys to use for the checkin key. See this file for more details.
+2. `config/settings.yml`: Stubs out a check-in key for each cron job. Since we may not want to have a check-in for all environments, this stub key will be used and produce a null check-in.

+4. HB notification page: Check-ins are configured per project in HB. To configure a check-in, the cron schedule will be needed, which can be found with `bundle exec whenever`. pull_request.title: Silence curl and simplify quoting
pull_request.body:
## Why was this change made? 🤔

cron on `preservation-catalog-prod-04` was sending email because curl's diagnostic output was being sent to stderr, which caused cron to think something was wrong. This change tells curl to be silent, and removes some of the unneeded quoting so that the cron entries are easier to read. The `:output` for runner_hb was also positioned earlier since curl will be quiet.

The two different styles of resulting cron entries now look like:

```
0 0 * * 3 /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221207173228 && bin/rails runner -e production "PreservedObject.archive_check_expired.find_each(&:audit_moab_version_replication!)" >> /dev/null 2>> log/c2a-err.log && curl --silent https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/rkIdpB'

0 * * * * /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221207173228 && RAILS_ENV=production bundle exec rake --silent "prescat:cache_cleaner:stale_files" >> /var/log/preservation_catalog/zip_cache_cleanup.log && curl --silent https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/2AIqEx'
```

Fixes #2102

## How was this change tested? 🤨

Tested crontab generation on QA.

⚡ ⚠ If this change has cross service impact, or if it changes code used internally for cloud replication, ***run [integration test preassembly_image_accessioning_spec.rb](https://github.com/sul-dlss/infrastructure-integration-test/blob/main/spec/features/preassembly_image_accessioning_spec.rb) against stage as it tests preservation***, and/or test in stage environment, in addition to specs. The main classes relevant to replication are `ZipmakerJob`, `PlexerJob`, `*DeliveryJob`, `ResultsRecorderJob`, and `DruidVersionZip`; [see here for overview diagram of replication pipeline](https://github.com/sul-dlss/preservation_catalog/blob/main/app/jobs/README.md).⚡

issue.title: Invalid crontab entry on preservation-catalog-prod-04
issue.body:
Cron on `pres@preservation-catalog-prod-04.stanford.edu` is reporting an error via email:

```
From: root@preservation-catalog-prod-04.stanford.edu (Cron Daemon)
To: pres@preservation-catalog-prod-04.stanford.edu
Subject: Cron <pres@preservation-catalog-prod-04> /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221206133618 && RAILS_ENV=production bundle exec rake prescat:cache_cleaner:stale_files --silent >> /var/log/preservation_catalog/zip_cache_cleanup.log && curl '\''https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/REDACTED'

/bin/bash: -c: line 0: unexpected EOF while looking for matching `''
/bin/bash: -c: line 1: syntax error: unexpected end of file
```

The crontab entry looks like:

```
0 * * * * /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221206133618 && RAILS_ENV=production bundle exec rake prescat:cache_cleaner:stale_files --silent >> /var/log/preservation_catalog/zip_cache_cleanup.log && curl '\''https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/REDACTED'
```

The quoting seems a bit unbalanced? I noticed it is also different than the equivalent HB crontab on `preservation-catalog-prod-02.stanford.edu`:

```
0 1 * * 0 /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221206133618 && bin/rails runner -e production '\''MoabStorageRoot.find_each(&:validate_expired_checksums!)'\'' && curl '\''https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/REDACTED'\'' >> /dev/null 2>> log/cv-err.log'
```

Perhaps this is related to our [recent integration](https://github.com/sul-dlss/preservation_catalog/pull/2075) of HoneyBadger into crontabs?

**User Impact**

It looks like there is little user impact, but if the zips aren't cleaned up presumably a filesystem will fill up and we'll start getting errors in Argo.

**Object(s) In This Error State**

It appears to only be affecting `preservation-catalog-prod-04`.

Steps to Reproduce, if Known:

Run the command in the crontab manually?

**Expected behavior**

For the cron to run without reporting errors via email.

+## Cron check-ins
+Some cron jobs (configured via the whenever gem) are integrated with Honeybadger check-ins. These cron jobs will check-in with HB (via a curl request to an HB endpoint) whenever run. If a cron job does not check-in as expected, HB will alert.
+
+Cron check-ins are configured in the following locations:
+1. `config/schedule.rb`: This specifies which cron jobs check-in and what setting keys to use for the checkin key. See this file for more details.

+4. HB notification page: Check-ins are configured per project in HB. To configure a check-in, the cron schedule will be needed, which can be found with `bundle exec whenever`. issue.body:
Ceph storage will be [upgraded by Ops](https://github.com/sul-dlss/operations-tasks/issues/3015) on December 4, 2022. 

This upgrade will test a process of pausing, not stopping, preservation robots and not shutting down preservation catalog.

issue.title: Invalid crontab entry on preservation-catalog-prod-04
issue.body:
Cron on `pres@preservation-catalog-prod-04.stanford.edu` is reporting an error via email:

```
From: root@preservation-catalog-prod-04.stanford.edu (Cron Daemon)
To: pres@preservation-catalog-prod-04.stanford.edu
Subject: Cron <pres@preservation-catalog-prod-04> /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221206133618 && RAILS_ENV=production bundle exec rake prescat:cache_cleaner:stale_files --silent >> /var/log/preservation_catalog/zip_cache_cleanup.log && curl '\''https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/REDACTED'

/bin/bash: -c: line 0: unexpected EOF while looking for matching `''
/bin/bash: -c: line 1: syntax error: unexpected end of file
```

The crontab entry looks like:

```
0 * * * * /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221206133618 && RAILS_ENV=production bundle exec rake prescat:cache_cleaner:stale_files --silent >> /var/log/preservation_catalog/zip_cache_cleanup.log && curl '\''https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/REDACTED'
```

The quoting seems a bit unbalanced? I noticed it is also different than the equivalent HB crontab on `preservation-catalog-prod-02.stanford.edu`:

```
0 1 * * 0 /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221206133618 && bin/rails runner -e production '\''MoabStorageRoot.find_each(&:validate_expired_checksums!)'\'' && curl '\''https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/REDACTED'\'' >> /dev/null 2>> log/cv-err.log'
```

Perhaps this is related to our [recent integration](https://github.com/sul-dlss/preservation_catalog/pull/2075) of HoneyBadger into crontabs?

**User Impact**

It looks like there is little user impact, but if the zips aren't cleaned up presumably a filesystem will fill up and we'll start getting errors in Argo.

**Object(s) In This Error State**

It appears to only be affecting `preservation-catalog-prod-04`.

Steps to Reproduce, if Known:

Run the command in the crontab manually?

**Expected behavior**

For the cron to run without reporting errors via email.

issue.title: Invalid crontab entry on preservation-catalog-prod-04
issue.body:
Cron on `pres@preservation-catalog-prod-04.stanford.edu` is reporting an error via email:

```
From: root@preservation-catalog-prod-04.stanford.edu (Cron Daemon)
To: pres@preservation-catalog-prod-04.stanford.edu
Subject: Cron <pres@preservation-catalog-prod-04> /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221206133618 && RAILS_ENV=production bundle exec rake prescat:cache_cleaner:stale_files --silent >> /var/log/preservation_catalog/zip_cache_cleanup.log && curl '\''https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/REDACTED'

/bin/bash: -c: line 0: unexpected EOF while looking for matching `''
/bin/bash: -c: line 1: syntax error: unexpected end of file
```

The crontab entry looks like:

```
0 * * * * /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221206133618 && RAILS_ENV=production bundle exec rake prescat:cache_cleaner:stale_files --silent >> /var/log/preservation_catalog/zip_cache_cleanup.log && curl '\''https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/REDACTED'
```

The quoting seems a bit unbalanced? I noticed it is also different than the equivalent HB crontab on `preservation-catalog-prod-04.stanford.edu`:

```
0 1 * * 0 /bin/bash -l -c 'cd /opt/app/pres/preservation_catalog/releases/20221206133618 && bin/rails runner -e production '\''MoabStorageRoot.find_each(&:validate_expired_checksums!)'\'' && curl '\''https://api.honeybadger.io/v1/check_in/REDACTED'\'' >> /dev/null 2>> log/cv-err.log'
```

Perhaps this is related to our [recent integration](https://github.com/sul-dlss/preservation_catalog/pull/2075) of HoneyBadger into crontabs?

**User Impact**

It looks like there is little user impact, but if the zips aren't cleaned up presumably a filesystem will fill up and we'll start getting errors in Argo.

**Object(s) In This Error State**

It appears to only be affecting `preservation-catalog-prod-04`.

Steps to Reproduce, if Known:

Run the command in the crontab manually?

**Expected behavior**

For the cron to run without reporting errors via email.
